2026-04-13 15:40:42,873 INFO RLM iteration 1/50
Reasoning: We need to add a formula that counts open cases per year. The formula should look at G14:G185 for the year and J14:J185 for the status "open". We'll place this formula in column I for each row 14‑185, preserving any existing formatting. If any merged cells intersect column I in that range, we'll unmerge them first. After modifying the workbook, we'll save it to the output directory with the same filename and set `output_spreadsheet` to that path.
Code:
```repl
import os
from pathlib import Path
from openpyxl import load_workbook

# Paths
input_path = Path(input_spreadsheet)  # /sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_41978_init.xlsx
output_dir = Path("/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet")
output_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
output_path = output_dir / input_path.name  # same filename

# Load workbook (preserve existing formatting)
wb = load_workbook(filename=input_path)  # default read/write mode keeps styles
ws = wb.active  # assume the first sheet is the target

# Unmerge any merged cells that intersect column I (9) rows 14-185
for merged_range in list(ws.merged_cells.ranges):
    # Get bounds
    min_col, min_row, max_col, max_row = merged_range.bounds
    # If column I (9) is within the merged range and rows overlap 14-185, unmerge
    if min_col <= 9 <= max_col and not (max_row < 14 or min_row > 185):
        ws.unmerge_cells(str(merged_range))

# Insert formula in column I for rows 14 to 185
for row in range(14, 186):
    # Build formula string
    formula = f'=COUNTIFS($G$14:$G$185, G{row}, $J$14:$J$185, "open")'
    cell = ws.cell(row=row, column=9)  # column I is 9
    cell.value = formula
    # Preserve existing style (openpyxl keeps style unless we replace the cell object)

# Save the modified workbook
wb.save(output_path)

# Set output variable for submission
output_spreadsheet = str(output_path)

# Print a quick verification summary
print(f"Saved modified workbook to: {output_path}")
print(f"Rows 14-185 in column I now contain formulas:")
for r in range(14, 19):  # show first few rows as sample
    print(f"I{r} = {ws.cell(row=r, column=9).value}")
```
